  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Package Dependencies**\n\nI\'m currently focused on dissecting the `package.json` file. My attention is drawn to the listed dependencies, like `express`, `@types/express`, and `esbuild`, as well as `@google/genai`. I\'ve also noted that I need to pay close attention to any custom `server.ts` updates, as the \"dev\" script needs to be updated.\n\n\n**Examining Build Scripts**\n\nI\'m now diving into the `package.json` scripts, specifically \"build\" and \"start\". This template pattern uses Vite for the frontend and a custom backend server. I\'m ensuring we can run a custom server with Vite middleware for development and static file handling for production. I need to make sure the server binds to `0.0.0.0` and port `3000`. I\'m now checking for data visualization dependencies. The instructions specifically mention `d3` and `recharts`. Let\'s confirm that Recharts is NOT installed, and then get it in the dependencies.\n\n\n**Considering Charting Libraries**\n\nI\'m now contemplating charting libraries. While D3 is an option, `recharts` seems like a strong choice for this React application, offering high quality and standard support. I\'ll use `install_applet_package` to integrate it. I\'m also considering the possibility of beautiful inline SVGs for their precision, responsiveness, and minimal dependencies. I need to make sure the library is compatible with React 19. Let\'s install `recharts` and its types. I see a line chart.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Visualizations**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the specific visualizations needed. I\'m leaning heavily towards custom, bug-free, and type-safe React-rendered SVGs for the area gradient in the Revenue vs Expenses chart and the Donut chart for Inventory Status with utilization. These SVGs can be exquisitely styled with Tailwind gradients. This is a solid solution. The mock\'s aesthetic will be perfectly replicated in the HTML. I\'m focused on developing mouse interactions such as tooltips and hovering, since React does this perfectly.\n\n\n**Defining Visualizations & Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now concretizing the specific charts and their interactive elements. I\'m focusing on \"Revenue vs Expenses,\" and I\'ll use a blue fill gradient and a dashed slate line for expenses. For the Donut Chart on inventory, I want full interactivity. I will show \"In Production,\" \"Low Stock,\" and \"Outbound.\" I want to add an interactive recent activities feed. I\'m also considering some quick actions and an \"Ask Nexus Anything\" AI widget. This design will be a great start!\n\n\n**Expanding Application Scope**\n\nI\'m now expanding the application\'s scope to include all sidebar pages for a fully functional ERP. I\'m prioritizing building stunning, interactive views for each section. This includes a fully interactive dashboard with quick action dialogs, detailed analytics charts with a growth slider, and a high-density inventory table.\n\n\n**Outlining Data Tables**\n\nI\'m now outlining data tables for a high-density inventory view and plan to show Item ID, Name, Category, Stock Level, Status, Warehouse Zone, and Last Updated. I\'m also adding \"Adjust Stock\" buttons, search, filters, and a \"Low Stock Alerts\" panel. I\'ve designed interactive production columns: \"Backlog\", \"Scheduled\", \"In Progress\", \"Quality Control\", \"Completed\", with a Trello-like board view. I\'ll add production batch forms, and track shipments with a map, a list of active shipments, and an \"Add New Shipment\" feature.\n\n\n"
